	(text_box "NOTE:\n\nThis module is designed to better display an analog signal originating from a source with moderately high output impedance (a few hundred ohms) to a visualizer or oscilloscope with moderately high input capacitance (tens of picofarads).\n\nIt supports a maximum bandwidth of up to 55 MHz (depending on the source impedance) and is primarily designed to display sine waves. However, it can also handle other waveforms, such as triangular and square waves. If the source impedance is sufficiently high (>= 470Ω), R1 can be shorted (removed). On the other hand, a ~1pF capacitor can be placed in parallel with R1 to minimize overshoot, undershoot, and ringing at the edges of the square wave, though this comes at the expense of rounding the leading and trailing edges at higher frequencies.\n\nNote that, while the signal's appearance should have better visual clarity, the output amplitude is typically 5% to 10% lower than the input. Additionally, due to the coupling capacitors, the output signal will be centered around GND."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 26.67 119.38 0)
		(size 243.84 39.37)
		(stroke
			(width 0)
			(type default)
			(color 0 0 255 1)
		)
		(fill
			(type none)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.905 1.905)
				(color 0 0 255 1)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "a7eec99d-b69b-49cc-8b8a-92b8e67d89d3")
	)
	(text_box "The LSK170 can also be used; however, the pin layout must be changed from DSG to SGD.\n\nhttps://www.linearsystems.com/_files/ugd/7e8069_a086ff7323054b5da3b91e364c90b3d4.pdf"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 127 25.4 0)
		(size 143.51 13.97)
		(stroke
